# Requirement

Source task: `elections_bc`

The generated interface should implement the following Vision2Web Level 2 frontend requirement.

I want to build an Elections BC website. When someone opens the site, they see a homepage with five main navigation sections: Provincial Elections, Candidates & Parties, Local Elections, Events & Services, and Resources. The homepage also features a prominent call-to-action button "Register to Vote" in the header, along with featured content blocks including a large banner for the 2024 Provincial Election Report with a "Learn more" button, and three smaller content cards for "2026 General Local Elections", "2024 B.C. Election Financing Reports", and "Contribution Limits", each with their own "Learn more" buttons.

If I click the "Register to Vote" button from the homepage header, it takes me to the voter registration page. On this page, I can learn about four different ways to register: online, by phone at 1-800-661-8683, by mail/fax/email by sending to this form, or in-person at the office at #100 – 1112 Fort St, Victoria, BC, V8V 3K8. The page explains the eligibility requirements and mentions that 16 and 17-year-olds can register as future voters and will be automatically added to the Provincial Voters List when they turn 18.

From the homepage, if I click the "Learn more" button on the 2024 Provincial Election Report banner, it takes me to the 2024 Provincial Election page. This page contains the official election report available in multiple volumes, including Volume I: Administration and Volume II: Financing and Expenses. I can also see election statistics showing that 2,109,658 voters cast their ballot, representing 58.45% of registered voters on October 19, 2024.

If I click on the "Learn more" button in the "2026 General Local Elections" card on the homepage, I'm taken to the 2026 General Local Elections page. This page tells me that the next general local elections will be held on October 17, 2026, and includes important dates such as the nomination period from September 1-11, 2026, and when the campaign period begins on September 19, 2026. The page explains that these elections cover positions for mayors and municipal councillors, regional district directors, school boards trustees, specified party boards, local community commissions, and the Islands Trust.

From the 2026 General Local Elections page, if I click on the "Local Forms" link in the left sidebar menu, I'm taken to the local election forms page. The forms page provides multiple categories of forms organized by type: Candidate forms for disclosure statements and financial agent appointments, Elector Organization forms for registration and annual reports, Third-Party Advertising Sponsor forms for registration and disclosure, and other specialized forms including Local Non-Campaign Voting Advertising Sponsor forms and Local Third Party Advertising Sponsor forms. All forms are available as fillable PDF documents.

From the homepage, if I click on the Resources link in the main navigation menu, I'm taken to the resources page. This page provides access to Maps, Forms & Guides, Results, Voters List, Reports, and Legislation through links in the left sidebar. The resources page explains that this section includes maps and other geography products, voting results and data from past electoral events, voters lists, reports of the Chief Electoral Officer and legislation.

Throughout the website, there is consistent access to the "Register to Vote" button in the header of every page. The site also provides footer links to Accessibility, Sitemap, Privacy, and Social Media Policy on all pages, along with contact information including phone numbers (Toll-Free: 1-800-661-8683, TTY: 1-888-456-5448), fax (Toll-Free Fax: 1-866-466-0665), and email (electionsbc@elections.bc.ca).


